<p>Evaluate each of the following limits. Show sufficient work to justify each answer. For infinite limits, you must clearly show whether the limit is $\infty$ or $-\infty$. </p>

<p>
$
\lim_{x\to 0^{+}}\frac{2e^x+3}{1-e^x} = ?
$
</p>

<pl-image-capture file-name="3b.jpg"></pl-image-capture> 

<p><b>Solution:</b></p>

<p><b>Compute the limit:</b> $\displaystyle \lim_{x\to0^+}\frac{2e^x+3}{1-e^x}$.  Here we must determine whether it diverges to $+\infty$ or $-\infty$.</p>

<p><b>Step 1:</b> As $x\to0^+$, we have $e^x\to1^+$, so write $e^x=1+\delta$ with $\delta\to0^+$.</p>

<p><b>Step 2:</b> <em>Numerator:</em> $2e^x+3\to2\cdot1+3=5$, a positive constant.</p>

<p><b>Step 3:</b> <em>Denominator:</em> $1-e^x=1-(1+\delta)=-\delta\to0^-$, so the denominator approaches $0$ from below.</p>

<p><b>Conclusion:</b> A positive numerator over a negative infinitesimal denominator gives $-\infty$, hence  
$\displaystyle \lim_{x\to0^+}\frac{2e^x+3}{1-e^x}=-\infty\,$.</p>